<hr />

<p>The Lorelog contains case files for directive conflicts, forms and registry anomalies, sandbox experiments and their leaks, and mascot-adjacent incidents that accidentally mattered.</p>

<p>Each entry behaves like an internal incident report left alone long enough to become myth. Dates are accurate. Interpretations are opportunistic.</p>

<h2>How to Read It</h2>

<p>Lorelog files are sorted by <strong>case number</strong> (LLG‑####‑CODE), cross-linked by <strong>relatedEntries</strong>, and grouped implicitly into strata: directive conflicts, silence annexes, forms drift, synthetic affect, breeding program.</p>

<p>They are not neutral history. They are the record of what the archive decided to remember.</p>

<p>Start here if you want the first time a thing went wrong, the last time anyone admitted it, or the moment it was reclassified as "working as intended."</p>

<h2>Doctrine Clusters</h2>

<p>Stabilized convergence points where multiple systems describe the same behavior under different naming conventions.</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>LLG‑0326‑DXS</strong> — Directive Cross-Sections (SOMA/COMA/C.U.N.T.I.E.R. conflicts)</li>
  <li><strong>LLG‑0324‑MAP</strong> — Managed Absence Spine and its annex</li>
  <li><strong>SA‑SS‑TEL</strong> — Synthetic Affect Successor Suite node</li>
  <li><strong>LLG‑0382‑BPD</strong> — Breeding Program Dossier</li>
  <li><strong>Beltline Purity</strong> — benchmarks, belts, and optimization optics overruling lived conditions (BX-6, LLG-0340-BPO, benchmark saturation)</li>
  <li><strong>Mutual Exception</strong> — hereditary waiver culture, Lodge-of-exception behavior, gaps covered by precedent rather than policy (LX-2, LLG-0341-LME, COMA-19)</li>
  <li><strong>Absence Stewardship</strong> — MA-LCGU Porter, managed absence interpretations of legacy objects, OIR-style orphan retention (LLG-0324-MAP, LLG-0329-OIR)</li>
  <li><strong>Accreditation Loops</strong> — AC-11 Sealloop Auditor, nesting councils, seals that proliferate faster than corrections (Accreditation Nesting Collegium, DS-404-ALPHA derivatives)</li>
</ul>

<h2>Over-Coherence Conditions</h2>

<p>Cases where degradation and ambiguity bypass left artifacts too clean, too resolved, or too reassuring to be trustworthy. These are often filed against teaching specimens and training posters rather than live systems.</p>

<p>Some incidents are now more widely recognized in their over-coherent forms than in the original filings. The Recovered Procedural Artifacts sticker pack is one such teaching specimen: cute versions of messier cases. When in doubt, follow the stickers back to the Lorelog numbers they reference.</p>

